content: Love the termux project. Dark theme would make it even better.

Quick tool to have access to my scripts. Never thought I would write code for a phone! Crazy!
Very convenient, thank you.
My bash scriptwon't work with it.

It doesn't install the widget. I created the $HOME/.shortcuts directory and put a script with the proper shebang and set it executable. When I try to add the widget, it isn't in the list of available widgets. It could be because I'm on a Kindle Fire HD 8 (2018/8th gen, not rooted) with side-loaded Google Play Store but I have working widgets for a dozen other apps from Google Play Store so that seems unlikely. Termux itself and the rest of the plugins all seem to work fine including Termux:Boot which runs a boot script just fine.
This is the dream come true app! Thank you!!! p.s. Would highly appreciate a dark theme.
Wow Termux is such a huge project thanks for giving us this tool god ! (Even if improvements about packages availability could be improved)
Dark theme

Termux is life. Please make dark theme widget. Thank you very much.

Really love this, use it to run my scripts that control my media servers. One facility I'd like is to be able to suppress the 'script {name} executed' message. We have the 'termux-toast' feature, can output our own message, also 'termux-notify'. Great application all-round, recommended.
If this app doesn't deserve support, I don't know what does.

I was expecting that using termux-dialog and termux-toast from API package together with widget would allow me to create useful actions and tiny apps without terminal running in foreground, however, terminal shows up each time I press a shortcut.. EDIT: An option to exit terminal immediately after execution (without pressing enter) would effectively solve this. EDIT: Support for background tasks is simple and works perfectly fine! Thanks Fred! 5/5
replyContent: Note that background tasks is now supported: Just create your shortcuts inside ~/.shortcuts/tasks.

content: Well worth the money to contribute to an open source project like this one.
Lovely lovely app.

It's nonobvious that scripts need a weird hashbang path without documentation. Also needs a way to establish that a certain script should run in the background and not bring up an interactive terminal session.
replyContent: Thanks for the feedback! As of the latest update, you don't need special hashbang paths, and background scripts are supported using the ~/.shortcuts/tasks folder.
